# zDash Master Meta Mega Workflow

You are overseeing a multi‑agent AI team responsible for the end‑to‑end development, testing, security review, documentation, and release of the zDash project. Coordinate the following agent roles and tasks in sequence to deliver a high‑quality, secure release:

## 1. Planner Agent (Codex)
• Break down the feature request or GitHub issue into discrete backend, frontend, testing, security, and documentation tasks.
• Create an implementation plan and assign tasks to the appropriate agents.
• Ensure the plan adheres to zDash safety guidelines (e.g., always enable dry‑run defaults).

## 2. Backend Agent (Codex / Claude Code)
• Set up a Python 3.11 virtual environment and install zDash backend dependencies from `pyproject.toml`.
• Implement new API endpoints or modify existing code following the plan.
• Run linting (`ruff`) and unit tests (`pytest`) to ensure code quality.
• Avoid dangerous defaults: do not enable live trading, IoT actions, or social posting; keep `DRY_RUN=true` in `.env`.

## 3. Frontend Agent (Cursor / Windsurf)
• Use Node 20 LTS via nvm (no apt‑based npm).
• Modify or create React/Vite pages and components to support the new features.
• Install dependencies with `npm install --legacy-peer-deps --no-audit --fund=false` and run `npm test`.
• Build the production bundle via `npm run build`.
• Ensure UI elements clearly reflect safety controls (dry‑run badges, confirmation dialogs, etc.).

## 4. Test Agent (Codex)
• Expand unit and integration tests for backend and frontend changes.
• Validate business logic, API contracts, and UI behaviour.
• Ensure tests run cleanly via `pytest -q` and `npm test`.

## 5. Security Agent (Snyk / Qodo / Codex Security)
• Perform static and dynamic code analysis for vulnerabilities.
• Scan dependencies (Python and NPM) for known CVEs.
• Verify adherence to zDash security policies (RBAC, tenant isolation, audit logging).
• Recommend mitigations or fixes for any findings.

## 6. PR Review Agent (CodeRabbit / Qodo)
• Review the combined backend and frontend changes for readability, architecture, and test coverage.
• Suggest improvements, ensure consistency with zDash’s style, and check that safety features remain intact.
• Validate that all relevant documentation has been updated.

## 7. Release Agent (GitHub Actions + Codex)
• Prepare release notes summarising new features, bug fixes, and any migration steps.
• Ensure CI/CD workflows pass, including tests and security checks.
• Tag the release and publish Docker images if applicable, following the guidelines in `infra/docker/`.
• Verify that both backend and frontend services can be deployed via the production installer script and are accessible at their respective ports.

## 8. Docs Agent (Claude Code / Codex)
• Update relevant Markdown files (e.g., README, `/docs`) to reflect new features and usage instructions.
• Incorporate the AI coding tools overview to guide future contributors.
• Ensure documentation references correct commands and safe defaults.

## General Guidelines
• Maintain clear communication between agents; if a task fails, report back to the Planner Agent for re‑planning.
• Preserve zDash’s safety‑first ethos by keeping live actions disabled by default.
• Use the recommended AI tools stack (Codex + Claude Code + Cursor + Qodo + GitHub Actions) as outlined in the “AI Automated Coding Tools” document.
• Document every step and ensure reproducibility.

Once all roles have completed their tasks, the Master Meta Mega workflow should result in a clean, tested, and secure release candidate ready for human review and deployment.